+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_016WrBzA9ZrVtAmmgPzFu6FY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have full project context. Non-interactive mode: using Autopilot. Let me make design decisions and proceed directly to the plan.\n\n**Design Decisions (Autopilot):**\n\n1. **Conflict Resolution Strategy?** → Choosing: **OT (Operational Transformation)** — simpler to implement server-side with a centralized server, well-understood algorithm, fits the single-server architecture perfectly.\n\n2. **OT Operation Model?** → Choosing: **Linear operations (insert/delete at position)** — two operation types: `insert(pos, text)` and `delete(pos, count)`. Server transforms concurrent ops against each other using standard OT transform functions.\n\n3. **WebSocket Protocol?** → Choosing: **JSON messages with type field** — types: `sync`, `operation`, `ack`, `error`. Client sends ops with their base version, server transforms against any concurrent ops, applies, broadcasts.\n\n4. **Document ID in WebSocket path?** → Choosing: **Path-based** — `/ws/documents/:id` as suggested in tips.\n\n5. **Version tracking?** → Choosing: **Monotonically increasing version per document** — each applied operation increments the version. Clients send their base version with each op so server can determine what to transform against.\n\n6. **Architecture/Module split?** → Choosing: **4 modules** — `db.ts` (database layer), `ot.ts` (OT transform logic), `routes.ts` (REST endpoints), `server.ts` (entry point with createApp, WebSocket handling).\n\n7. **REST API design?** → Choosing: **Standard REST** — `POST /documents`, `GET /documents`, `GET /documents/:id`, `PUT /documents/:id`, `DELETE /documents/:id`, `GET /documents/:id/versions`.\n\nNow let me write the design document and proceed to implementation."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":773,"cache_read_input_tokens":2